  "prompt": "Can I get into grad school with 2 C's?",
  "response": "Yes, you can get into grad school with two C's, but your chances may vary depending on several factors such as the overall strength of your application, the prestige and competitiveness of the program you are applying to, and any additional qualifications you might have. \n\nAdmissions committees look at a variety of factors including your GPA, letters of recommendation, statement of purpose, relevant work experience, research experience, standardized test scores (like GRE), and extracurricular activities. If you have strong qualifications in these other areas, it can help compensate for having received two C's.\n\nIt's also a good idea to explain any extenuating circumstances that may have led to the lower grades in your personal statement, if applicable. Showing resilience and how you've improved academically or professionally can be beneficial.\n\nResearch the specific requirements and average profiles of admitted students for the programs you are interested in to better gauge your chances and tailor your application accordingly.",
